# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aintree-racecourse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The **1836 Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the first of three unofficial annual precursors of a steeplechase which later became known as the Grand National.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The steeplechase was held at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool, England on 29 February 1836 and attracted a field of ten runners.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The winning horse was The Duke, ridden by Captain Martin Becher in the violet with white sleeves and cap colours of Mr Sirdefield, the landlord of the *George Inn* in Great Crosby and was trained privately.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was won in a time of 15 minutes 12 seconds, over twice the present course record.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was a selling race and its status as an official Grand National was revoked some time between 1862 and 1873.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] For many years the course set for this race was thought to be at Maghull, with even the honours board at Aintree stating such.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] However, contemporary reports state with no doubt that the course was Aintree, and the same, which was used for every other race bar those, which took place at Gatwick during the First World War.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The Start was at the same point where most Nationals would commence from the 1860s until the early 21st century, just in front of the stands, facing out towards the line of country the runners would take.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] There was no set number of created fences and instead the runners had to navigate a course as best they could.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] What potential obstacles they encountered along the way could be either jumped or navigated around, just as long as they remained outside a set of flags, which marked the inner line of the course.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Therefore running around a fence, would not disqualify a horse as it would today.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The course had many lanes around it that a rider could take if they felt it more advantageous than jumping the banks from field to field.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The potential obstacles they would encounter if they followed the expected line of country to be run.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] **Fence 1** A formidable bank out of a lane topped with furze, **Fence 2** Stiff fence, **Fence 3** Stiff fence, **Fence 4** Stiff fence, **Fence 5** Brook.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] However, there were several lanes and gates a competitor could navigate around the Canal side of the course, avoiding many of these fences.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] If they jumped them all then the last fence before entering the race course proper again would be **Fence 12** An awkward rail onto a paved road.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The runners then had a half mile to cover to reach **Fence 13** Stiff hurdle well matted with furze, **Fence 14** Stiff hurdle well matted with furze.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] They then passed the grandstand and would cover the same ground again.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race got off to a poor start when all ten runners refused at the first obstacle, *Derry* turning and leading the way at the second attempt.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Once past that, the field continued around the first circuit without incident, although *Gulliver* and *Cowslip* were tailed off and looking distressed when they came back in sight in front of the stands, both being pulled up, rather than take the second circuit.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Prior to the race it was ordered that one particular gate out of a lane near the paved road would remain nailed open so that the runners could pass.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] However, one spectator took exception to this and either by design, or just not realising, freed and closed the gate after the first circuit.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Horatio Powell, on board the favourite, *Laurie Todd* took this route on the first circuit and again on the second, not expecting the gate ahead to now be closed.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The obstacle proved too high for the favourite to jump and the horse became the first to fall in the race.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Powell was quickly on his feet and making a bid to remount when another competitor, Most likely Bretherton aboard *Cock-A-Hoop*, knocked him back to the ground.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] While there appears to have been some whispers that this act was deliberate, the fact Powell made no objection after the race suggest he at least believed the collision to have been mere accident.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Either way, *Laurie Todd* backer's had lost their money.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The chances of *Cock-A-Hoop* and *Percy* were fading by this stage as they were losing ground on the two leaders and by the time they came in sight of the stands, they were battling for third pace.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Both were briefly offered hope as the two leaders, *The Duke* and *Polyanthus* both blundered at the final hurdle before going on to dispute the finish.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] *The Duke* prevailed by one length with *Polyanthus* finishing second.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was completed in fifteen minutes and 12 seconds, taking almost half as long again as the course would be covered in an average future Grand National, suggesting it was either cantered at a very slow pace or the runners encountered more issues than the reporters on course recorded.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race largely failed to capture the public imagination and came in for scathing comments from some of the local press.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] By the time the first Grand National historians began emerging in the early 1860s this race, and the two which would follow in 1837 and 1838, had largely been forgotten by the passing of time and fading memories.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] As a result, when the first honours board was erected at Aintree in the early 1890s this race was totally omitted and remained forgotten for over a century before being rediscovered early in the 21st century.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] It is still regarded officially by Aintree as not being worthy of Grand National status and is instead regarded as the first of three unofficial precursors over the same course.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The **1837 Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the second of three unofficial annual precursors of a Handicap Steeple-chase, later to become known as the Grand National Steeplechase horse race which took place at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool on 4 March 1837 and attracted a field of four runners.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] This race did not carry the prestige of the future Grand Nationals and its status as an official Grand National was revoked some time between 1862 and 1873.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Four horses lined up for the start of the race for which starting prices were recorded by the Liverpool Mail.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was won in a time of fourteen minutes, beating the previous year's time by five minutes and fifty seconds.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race would go on to be regarded as the second running of the Grand National until the mid-1860s when newspapers began omitting the race, and those of 1836 and 1838, from the records of previous winners.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Although it is now widely acknowledged that the race was indeed run at Aintree, it is also the official view of Aintree that the races prior to 1839 should not be included as legitimate Grand Nationals and should be regarded more as precursors.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] As a result, *The Duke* is not listed in official publications as a dual winner of the race.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] This race did not carry the prestige of the future Grand Nationals and its status as an official Grand National was revoked sometime between 1862 and 1873.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Three competitors faced the starter and were quoted as follows.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race had been delayed due to the weather and the resulting clash with the much more prestigious St Albans chase saw a field of competitors that failed to capture the imagination of the public.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The waning finances of the race organiser, William Lynn resulted in a committee being formed to try to boost the race.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] For many years after this event the race was regarded as the third running of the Grand National by racegoers and pressmen alike, however this stance began to change during the 1860s when national newspapers began listing the former winners of the National back only as far as 1839.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] When the official honours board at Aintree was erected in 1894 it stated that the race of 1838 was run at a nearby course in Maghull and that the winner was a horse named Sir Henry, ridden by Mr Olliver against nine rivals.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Racing returns from this period show that racing at Maghull ceased in 1835 and that there was no horse in training in 1838 named Sir Henry.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The only jockey named Olliver in racing at the time was Tom Olliver and on the date of the race he was riding at St Albans.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] For over a century the detail recorded on the honours board was accepted as fact until evidence was presented to show the real events of the 1838 Great Liverpool chase.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] While it is now accepted among the majority of racing writers that the 1838 race was indeed run at Aintree and not Maghull it is still the official view that the lack of prestige in the race prior to 1839 warrants its continued omission from being declared an official Grand National.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] The **1839 Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the first official annual running of a steeplechase which later became known as the Grand National.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] It was held at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool, England, on Tuesday 26 February 1839 and attracted a field of 17 runners.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the fourth running of the Grand Liverpool Steeplechase, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs possibly run at Maghull.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] This year the race came under new management and the arrival of the railway in Liverpool made travel to the course easier.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] The race was not run as a handicap chase (the Grand National was converted to a handicap race in 1843) and therefore all the runners carried twelve stone.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Eighteen runners were declared to run in the race but shortly before the start Jerry was withdrawn.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] The start was situated near to where the modern day Melling Road is and took the runners out into open countryside, jumping a line of natural banks, no more than 2 feet (0.61 m) high before reaching a post and rails over a brook.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] They then took the runners left towards the Leeds and Liverpool Canal, turning sharply (where the modern day Canal Turn is) to run along the canalside back towards the racecourse, negotiating the Second Brook (the modern day Valentine's Brook).
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] The runners would then enter the 'racecourse proper' at the far end of the circuit to run back towards the stands, jumping a plain fence (the modern day Chair) before jumping a wall topped with gorse (the modern day Water Jump).
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] The field then took another circuit of the course, this time bypassing the final two obstacles towards the finishing post.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Paulina refused the first jump but continued after being put at the fence a second time.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] The most famous incident of the race occurred at the fence then known as the First Brook.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Captain Becher had taken Conrad into second place at this stage but his mount failed to clear the rails and fell.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Becher was forced to dive for cover into the brook itself as the other horses cleared the obstacle and legend has it that he was heard to tell the spectators that he did not realise how filthy water tasted without the benefit of whisky.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Seconds later, William McDonough joined Becher in the brook after falling from Rust but it was the Captain's name attributed to the fence, now known as Becher's Brook.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Both riders remounted but Becher's race ended when his mount fell again at the Second Brook where both Barkston and Cannon Ball had also fallen.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] It was one of these horses, while running loose, who ended the hopes of the favourite when The Nun was brought down shortly before rejoining the racecourse; she was remounted by Tom Ferguson while Rust was pulled up before reaching the stands.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Charity fell at the wall in front of the stands but was also remounted.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Railroad led at this stage with Lottery in second place but so slow was the pace of the race and so wide the distances between competitors that the favourite The Nun had managed to make up ground to move into third.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] On the second circuit, Charity fell before reaching the First Brook for the second time while Dictator fell at the fence situated at the turn by the canal but was quickly remounted by Robert Carlin.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Jem Mason took Lottery into the lead at the First Brook and maintained it to the finish, winning more easily than the three-length margin suggested in a time of 14 minutes 53 seconds, 53 seconds outside the course record.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Lottery was prepared for the race at the stables of George Dockeray in Epsom, who is loosely regarded as the trainer but most of the preparation was more likely conducted by the owner, Piccadilly horse dealer John Elmore in whose colours of blue jacket and black cap the jockey rode.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Seventy-Four was second, Paulina third and True Blue fourth.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Pioneer was on course to finish third when he unseated his rider.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Walker quickly remounted but could only manage fifth place.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Although regarded at the time as the fourth running of the Grand Liverpool Steeplechase, this running went on to be regarded as the first official running of the Grand National.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] The finishing order was only loosely recorded in the press as Jack in sixth, The Nun seventh, Railroad eighth, Rambler ninth and Cramp the last of ten to pass the post.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] Later record books show seven finishers though this is not supported by any press reports from the time.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] There was also much criticism in the press over the severity of the event, especially the conduct of Robert Carlin in remounting Dictator when witnesses described the horse as distressed.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] His cause of death was recorded as a burst blood vessel.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] For many years it was believed that the silks worn by Mason were blue with black cap.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] However, when the original silks were restored and presented to the Aintree museum, they were found to have actually been scarlet.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1839-grand-national] It was found that John Elmore changed his colours to blue in the late 1840s, which led to the mistaken belief.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the fifth running of the Grand Liverpool, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The race was not run as a handicap chase and therefore all the runners were declared to carry 12 stone.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The course was laid out with eleven obstacles in total with the competitors starting from the bend at the end of the finishing straight beside the stables.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The first obstacle was an iron rail of 3 feet 5 inches into the Melling Road.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The runners then jumped out of the road over a hedge and ditch 7 feet 11 inches high.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The third fence was also a ditch some ten feet wide and the fourth an even bigger ditch of 16 feet to clear.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Fence five was a slightly smaller ditch before the runners cleared an obstacle of little consequence to be considered an actual fence.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The fence that would gradually come to be known as Becher's Brook was next with a clearance of 20 feet.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The runners then turned sharply towards the Canal over a considerable jump with a steep landing side.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The eighth fence was the second brook and ran along the canal side, this was followed by a ditch and rail with a thirteen-foot span.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The tenth fence was a leap into the Anchor Bridge and almost instantly straight back out again to bring the runners back towards the stands and the only fence on the course, a dry stone wall rising from 4 foot 6 inches to 4 foot 10 on the outside.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The runners then set off to jump the first ten fences, along with other insignificant obstacles before bypassing the wall on the run to the finish post.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The majority of the course was plough land with turf only on the racecourse proper and it was speculated by witnesses that the majority of the fences had been lowered slightly from last year in the wake of criticism.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The competitors reached the newly named Becher's Brook without incident where **Cruickshank** stumbled on landing and was cannoned into by **Weathercock** with both falling.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The former was remounted by his jockey, Guy, albeit with a severely bloodied nose while the latter's rider, Barker was carried unconscious to Seed's farmhouse nearby.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Last year's champion **Lottery** reached the stone wall in front of the stands in second place but clipped the top of the obstacle, falling amid a flurry of dismantled masonry.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] All three horses following immediately behind were caught in the melee and were brought down, the three being **Columbine**, favourite **The Nun** and **Seventy-four**.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Powell remounted the favourite but was forced to pull up before setting off on the second circuit when she was found to be lame while Olliver was taken to the stands with a broken collar bone and concussion.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The pileup allowed **Valentine** to re-establish a lead of many lengths over the rest of the field but he was caught shortly before reaching Becher's for the second time by **Jerry** and **Arthur** with the remaining competitors too far behind to be able to issue a challenge.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] **Arthur** fell heavily at the brook, leaving **Jerry** to canter home over the remaining fences to win as he liked.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] **Arthur** was quickly remounted and although he caught **Valentine** before jumping the final hurdle he was unable to make up the ground on **Jerry** and finished second by four lengths with **Valentine** the same distance behind in third.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The remaining runners had not reached the distance chair situated beside the wall fence by the time the third horse had passed the post, thus these runners were officially declared as non finishers.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Those who did pass the post were, in order, **Cruickshank**, **Hasty**, **The Sea** and **Spolasco**.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The last horse had fallen during the second circuit and was remounted while **The Augean** also fell at some point during the second circuit.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Despite winning in a very comfortable manner, and slowing to a canter a long way before the finish, **Jerry** still finished in a time of twelve minutes and thirty seconds, shattering the course record by a minute and a half.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Again the press were very critical of the race, especially noting the incident at the wall where many spectators had thought Tom Olliver had been killed by his fall, so bad was his state when being carried away to the stands.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Furthermore, it was later discovered that Barker had been left unattended in a barn near Seed's farm where none of the connections of his mount had made any enquiry as to his state.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] As a result, the wall was replaced with a water jump in time for the next running.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] Later historical accounts of the Grand National are notorious for carrying factual errors.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1840-grand-national] The official history of the race written in the 1980s recorded Cruickshank as a non runner and The Sea as an official finisher in fourth place.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the sixth running of the Grand Liverpool, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] The race was not run as a handicap chase and therefore all the runners were declared to carry 12 stone with the exception of the winner of the 1840 Cheltenham Steeplechase who had to carry 13 stone 4 lbs.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] The runners would set off from a grass field near Seeds lane and jump a small first fence before turning slightly right to jump a further four fences down a line of wheat fields to the first brook, described only as being familiar to Captain Beecher.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] The runners then proceeded left over a fallow field to take the seventh jump into a grass field to turn sharp left at the eighth obstacle, later to be known as the Canal Turn.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] Three further flights followed along the Canalside that took the runners over a large grass enclosure before jumping into and then out of the Melling Lane to re-enter the racecourse at its far extreme, known as the training ground.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] Once back in front of the stands, the runners took a hurdle at the site of the distance judge before leaping an artificial brook, which had replaced the wall, being the fifteenth obstacle.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] The competitors would then cover the same course again, with the exception of the artificial brook, which was bypassed on the run-in.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] The course was as it had been the previous year with the exception that the wall, situated in front of the stands, was replaced with an artificial water jump.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] Officially **Lottery** is recorded as favourite on officially good going.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] The race was started two hours late at 3 pm with **Selim** setting off at a pace considered good for a flat race.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] He earned a ten-length advantage by Becher's Brook and was still travelling well when he was considered unlucky to land on boggy ground when jumping out of the last fallow field into the grass at the Canalside, the eleventh jump on the course, causing him to fall and lose his lead.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] On turning back out into the country for the second time **Legacy** took up the running again.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] **Cigar**, **Peter Simple** and **Oliver Twist** adopted a different route down to Becher's Brook to the rest of the runners and bypassed the first jump, which was allowed, as long as the competitors raced outside the course marking flags.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] However, no real advantage, other than missing one fence, appears to have been made and the two groups were quickly reunited to jump the remaining fences to Becher's.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] By this stage **Selim** had made up the ground lost when falling and went back into the lead at the fence before the Brook.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] At the fence before the Canal Turn **Oliver Twist** fell and may have hampered **Cigar** who was the only runner continuing who was detached from the main body, but he was able to get back the lost lengths to move into second behind **Charity** when **Selim** began to fade along the Canalside.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] **Cigar**, **Charity** and **Lottery** jumped the fence out of the lane together before **Charity** kicked on to three-length lead on entering the racecourse.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] Most of the field had every chance at this stage but the injection of pace now told on most of the competitors, and with a quarter-mile to run **Charity** had only the two greys in the race **Peter Simple** and **Cigar** challenging him.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] Note: No official returns were given for any runner outside the first three.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] Four competitors claimed to have finished fourth in a tight finish, in which the decision was given to Revealer.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] No attempt was made to place the other three officially.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] The remaining runners, with the exception of Lottery, completed the course but had been stopped to a walk long before the finish and were swallowed up by the spectators, who entered the racecourse after the race.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1841-grand-national] At the time, horses swallowed up by the crowd in such a manner were listed as distanced.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] The 1842 **Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the fourth official annual running of a steeplechase, later to become known as the Grand National Steeplechase, a horse race which took place at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool on 2 March 1842 and attracted 15 runners.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the seventh running of the Grand Liverpool, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs and are today regarded as unofficial.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] The remaining runners did not command a starting price from the bookmakers and were sent off unquoted.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] The course consisted of two circuits of a spindle-shaped course at Aintree, starting from a position beyond the modern Melling Road, then known as the Sunken Lane, and into open countryside.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] The competitors would have to negotiate any hedges and banks they came across to travel from field to field, most of which were open ploughland, until reaching Becher's Brook, a man-made post and rail.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] From here the field then turned left towards the Leeds to Liverpool canal, before jumping the Canal Turn, a fence at a sharp 90-degree angle.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] This would then place the runners in the fields running along the canal, where they would jump Valentine's Brook, The Tabletop, a fence in which the landing side was significantly raised, and then across the lane at Anchor Bridge to re-enter the racecourse.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] From here, the land was laid to turf as the runners turned left and came back towards the stands.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] Here they had to negotiate the monument or make a fence, today known as the chair, and then a water jump before setting off on a second circuit of the course.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] The start of the second circuit was marked by the Sunken Lane, a bank into and then out of what is now Melling Road.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] The rest of the second circuit was the same as the first until turning back onto the racecourse.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] On reaching the race course for a second time, the runners would this time jump two hurdles before a long run into the finish line, bypassing the monument fence and water jump on the way.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] At the start of the second circuit, **Honesty** refused at the bank out of the Sunken Lane, where **Satirist** also fell.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] **Peter Simple** took up the running, and by the time Becher's Brook was reached for the second time, the competitors were spread out over a furlong of the course.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] At the turn for home a group of spectators, keen to get a good view, had encroached onto the course without realising.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] **Peter Simple** was by now many lengths clear but his rider failed to notice the spectators in time and in trying to avoid them he was thrown from his mount.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] Powell, on second-placed **Seventy Four** was able to take evasive action and continued towards the hurdles in the lead with only **Gaylad** close enough to challenge.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] The race was timed at 13 minutes and 30 seconds, a full minute outside the record.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] Colours as published in *The Liverpool Mail*, Thursday 3 March 1842.
[src:aintree-racecourse/1842-grand-national] Distanced refers to horses that was not in the sight of the judge when the first horse reached the chair.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Horse racing was popular in Liverpool from at least Tudor times, In the 18th century Nicholas Blundell organised races on the sands at Crosby.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1829, William Lynn, the owner of the Waterloo Hotel in Ranelagh Street, Liverpool, approached the Second Earl of Sefton, William Philip Molyneux, whose nickname was 'Lord Dashalong', about leasing land to organise flat racing.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] He laid the foundation stone on 7 February 1829, and placed a container of sovereigns inside the footings.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Lynn built a grandstand in time for the first meeting at Aintree racecourse on 7 July 1829, designed by John Foster Jr.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The opening race was the Croxteth Stakes over 1 mile 2 furlongs, and was won by Mufti.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1835 Lynn organised hurdle racing, which was a great success, especially when a well-known, rider, Captain Martin Becher, agreed to take part and rode a horse named Vivian to two victories.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The story goes that Becher told Lynn about the Great St.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Albans Steeplechase, a four-mile point-to-point race across country, which was first run in 1830.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] This caught Lynn's imagination and he decided that he wanted a similar race at Aintree.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] With Becher's help Lynn organised the Liverpool Grand Steeplechase, first run on 29 February 1836.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There were ten runners, to be ridden by gentlemen riders only, all carrying twelve stone, with the winner, sold if demanded. for two hundred sovereigns.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Captain Becher (after whom Becher's Brook is named) rode The Duke to victory.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The winner was owned by Mr Sirdfield, landlord of the George Inn at Great Crosby.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Some racing historians regard this 1836 race as the first Grand National, but most favour the 1839 event as the inaugural one.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Duke won again in 1837, Sir William in 1838.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There is even some disagreement as to the venue for the 1836 to 1838 races, with the nearby Maghull (which was opened in 1827 by a landowner, John Formby) having its supporters.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] By 1839 the aristocracy was taking an interest: Lords Derby, Eglinton, Wilton, Sefton and Lord George Bentinck backed a national racing event at Aintree.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The race was named the 'Grand Liverpool Steeplechase' and advertised as being "four miles across country" – though starting and finishing on the established racecourse.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] As he came out of the brook, Becher is reputed to have said that "water is no damned use without brandy!" Lottery, ridden by Jem Mason, won at 9/1, followed by Seventy-Four and Paulina, both 12/1.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The 6/1 favourite, The Nun, failed to finish.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] That first 'National' attracted a crowd of about 50,000.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In the following years the race became very popular, though William Lynn's health suffered and his interest in racing lessened.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Another member of the syndicate, Edward William Topham, who was also a racing handicapper, took over as the leading influence at Aintree.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1843 he turned the 'National' from a weight-for-age race into a handicap.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The race officially became the 'Grand National' in 1847; the following year Topham took on the lease of the course from Lord Sefton.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Grand National, and with it Aintree racecourse grew in popularity throughout the second half of the 19th century.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The 'National' was, by a long way, the most valuable and most important race in the national hunt calendar.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Grand National returned to Aintree in 1919.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] During the Second World War there was one race won by BOGSCAR in 1940 at Aintree as the course had been requisitioned for use as a storage depot with hundreds of servicemen from the USA being stationed there.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The course opened again on 4 April 1946 for the Spring Meeting, with the Grand National being run on the Friday, the second day of the three-day meeting.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Tophams bought the racecourse outright from Lord Sefton after leasing the course for 100 years.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] To celebrate this purchase, the Topham Trophy, a handicap steeplechase over 2 miles 6 furlongs of the Grand National course was introduced as the main race on the first day of the National meeting.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In December 1953 the Mildmay steeplechase course was opened with smaller versions of the Grand National fences.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] This two-day fixture was the first all National Hunt meeting ever staged at Aintree.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In July 1964 Mrs Topham announced that she intended selling the racecourse to a property developer, Capital & Counties, to build housing.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] This started the era of the "last Grand National" which lasted for about twenty years.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There was talk of the Grand National being transferred to Doncaster.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] 1973 saw the last Grand National meeting run by the Topham family as Aintree was bought by a local property developer, Bill Davies.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] A low ebb was reached in 1975 when the attendance at the Grand National was the lowest anyone could remember, largely because Bill Davies tripled admission prices.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The National meeting was revived in 1976 under Ladbrokes' management and a new clerk of the course, John Hughes (although Bill Davies still owned the course).
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The first day of the Spring Meeting saw the final flat race run at Aintree, the Knowsley Stakes over 1 mile 5 furlongs; the final two days, including Grand National day were all National Hunt events.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1977 all three days of the 'National' meeting were National Hunt for the first time, and have continued to be so.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The uncertainty about the future of the course was finally removed in December 1983 when the Jockey Club bought the course from Bill Davies.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Most of Aintree's old stands were demolished in 1985, leaving just the County Stand, which is grade II listed.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] A temporary stand, the Aintree Stand, was erected.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The County Stand was renovated and extended in 1988.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Three years later the temporary stands were replaced by a permanent one, opened by and named after the Queen Mother.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1993, the race was not held due to a series of false starts due to issues with the tape.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] One false start was not noticed by thirty of the thirty-nine runners due to the starter's flag failing to unfurl, with seven runners completing the course.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1995 Red Rum, the only horse to win the Grand National three times, died in October and was buried near the winning post.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] A statue to the horse had been unveiled at the course on Grand National day in 1988.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1997 part of the County Stand was demolished to prepare for a new grandstand.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Also in 1997, the race was postponed to Monday because of an IRA bomb threat.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1998 a new stand, named after the Princess Royal, was opened.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] 2006 saw the start of extensive re-development of the racecourse.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] A new parade ring, weighing room and winners' enclosure were opened.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The old weighing room was turned into a wine bar and museum.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] A year later two further grandstands were opened, named after the Earl of Derby and Lord Sefton.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 2015 the old weighing room and winners' enclosure were named 'McCoys' to honour the jockey A.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] McCoy, who had ridden in his final Grand National.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 2023, the race was delayed because of the Animal Rising protesters.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Grand National course is a left-handed triangular shaped course of about 2 miles 2 furlongs, with 16 fences, including three open ditches and a water jump.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The fences range in height from 4 ft 6 ins to 5 ft 2 ins ('The Chair', one of the open ditches, and the largest fence on the course).
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Some of the fences have a drop – a lower landing side than take off side.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] These include Becher's Brook, the 6th and 22nd fence in the Grand National, although its drop has been reduced in recent years.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] It is regarded as the most difficult of all courses to complete successfully, with the fences including obstacles such the Chair, Foinavon, Valentine's, Canal Turn and Becher's Brook.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] All fences bar the water jump are covered with spruce, unlike at any other course in British National Hunt racing.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Four other races take place over the National fences.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] These are the Topham Trophy Chase (reverting to its original name in 2002 after being known as the John Hughes Trophy Chase since 1989) and the Fox Hunters' Chase at the Grand National meeting, and the Grand Sefton Handicap Chase and Becher Chase in the December meeting.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The fences have been modified down the years to make them less severe.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1961 all the plain fences were sloped on the take-off side.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1990 the brooks at Becher's and Valentine's were filled in, while the landing side of Becher's was raised to reduce the drop.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 2011 the drop on the landing side of the first fence was reduced, and the height of the fourth fence was reduced by two inches for 4 ft 10 in.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In the same year the drop at Becher's was reduced again, by four to five inches.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Mildmay Course was named in honour of Lord Mildmay (1909-1950), who was champion amateur jockey four times and rode in several Grand Nationals.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] He felt there should be a 'nursery' course at Aintree, with smaller versions of the 'National' fences to provide an introduction to potential future runners in the Grand National to Aintree's unique fences.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The course opened in December 1953 with a two-day Yuletide meeting.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The benefit of the Mildmay course was that it enabled Aintree for the first time to stage all National Hunt cards.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Previously it could hold only flat programmes or mixed meetings of flat and jumps races.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The course, a left-handed oval, was a little over 1 mile 2 furlongs round, with eight fences, two of which were used in the Grand National: fence number 13 and 29 in the Grand National, which was the second of the four plain fences in the home straight on the Mildmay Course, and the water jump.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There were three fences along the back straight: an open ditch, a plain fence and another open ditch.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Races were run over two distances: 2 miles 80 yards, and 3 miles 1 furlong 130 yards.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The course was not popular with most trainers, and the races on the Mildmay course attracted small fields.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Mildmay course was used only once at the Grand National meeting, for the Mildmay 'Chase, a race over 2 miles 80 yards for novices, on the second day of the meeting.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1975 Bill Davies replaced the spruce fences of the Mildmay course with standard birch fences.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 1990 the Mildmay course was changed: the water jump was no longer used, while a 'cross fence' on the bend into the home straight replaced one of the plain fences in the home straight, creating a long run between the final two fences.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There were now four fences down the back straight, including an open ditch.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Hurdles' Course was the flat course, and is the oldest of Aintree's three courses.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] It is a left-handed oval of about 1 mile 3 furlongs, with sharp bends.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There are six flights of hurdles: three down the back straight, three in the home straight.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The final flat race at Aintree took place on the first day of the Grand National meeting in 1976.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Flat races of five furlongs were run on a straight course which ran diagonally across the centre of the Mildmay course.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] On this course on 7 April 1967, on the day before the Foinavon Grand National, on his first visit to Aintree, the two-year-old Red Rum, ridden by Paul Cook, dead-heated with Curlicue in a five-furlong selling plate.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The running rails for this course remained in place until 1987.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The Grand National race was run for many years over 4 miles 856 yards (4 miles 3 furlongs 196 yards), then 4 miles 4 furlongs.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In 2013 the start was moved 110 yards to keep the horses away from the noise of the crowd before the start.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The distance of the race is now 4 miles 514 yards (6.907 km) after being re-measured by the British Horseracing Authority in 2015.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The race is considered among the most demanding steeplechases in the world.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The lead has often changed hands during the 494-yard (452 m) run-in after the final fence.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There are usually 40 horses taking part in the race (this has been the maximum since 1984) but fewer than ten may actually complete the course: for example, 42 horses started in 1928, and only two reached the finishing post.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The record for the most victories in the Grand National is held by Red Rum, who won three times in the 1970s, in addition to coming second twice.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] There were several disruptions at Aintree Racecourse starting with the 1993 Grand National and it was not held because of a series of false starts.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The 1997 Grand National was postponed to Monday because of an IRA bomb threat which led the evacuation of 60,000 people and the 2023 Grand National was disrupted by the Animal Rising protesters.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The UK animal rights campaign group, Animal Aid, has been monitoring fatalities at racecourses since 2007, and in that time has recorded 75 deaths at Aintree.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] 51 of these deaths occurred during the April Aintree Festival, 12 of which happened during the Grand National race itself.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Aintree racecourse features in *Jump!* a novel by Jilly Cooper.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Aintree has also been used as a venue for motor racing.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The British Grand Prix was staged there on five occasions, in 1955, 1957, 1959, 1961 and 1962.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] In addition to the Grand Prix, the circuit also held 11 non-championship Formula 1 races, known as the Aintree 200, first won by Stirling Moss in 1954 with the last winner being Jack Brabham, in April 1964.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The only driver to have competed in both horse and motor races at Aintree is Alfonso de Portago, who rode in the Grand National in 1950 and 1952 as well as driving a Ferrari 750 Monza in the Daily Telegraph International Meeting in October 1955.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] He was set to compete at the 1957 British Grand Prix at Aintree, but he was killed in the Mille Miglia in May of that year.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The racecourse contains a 9-hole golf course and driving range within its boundaries.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Features such as Becher's Brook are incorporated into the course.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] It is accessed from Melling Road, which bisects the racecourse.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Because of this, the golf facilities are closed when the course is used for horse or motor racing.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Aintree racecourse was served by two railway stations: Aintree Racecourse railway station, which opened in about 1890, and Aintree Sefton Arms, which opened in 1849.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] The racecourse station was last used on Grand National day, 25 March 1961, and closed a year later.
[src:aintree-racecourse/aintree-racecourse] Aintree Sefton Arms became Aintree in 1968 and remains open.
